# Bug report

## Describe the bug

V2 currently breaks our usage from a nodejs desktop application. This is not a web server that uses the private token in admin mode, nor does it "impersonate" a client using setAuthheader. It's a standalone desktop application that uses auth.signInWithPassword();

The sign in attempt is succesfull, but none of the db related methods seem to utilize the session. Only the realtime module "sees" the session.

## To Reproduce

Steps to reproduce the behavior, please provide code snippets or a repository:

1. Create a completely empty node js app
2. Install Supabase JS V2 (RC10 at the time of writing)
3. create an index.js file and inside do:

```
const { createClient } = require("@supabase/supabase-js");

const client = createClient("INSERT_HOST_HERE", "INSERT_PUBLIC_ANON_KEY_HERE");

client.auth.onAuthStateChange((event, session) => {
  if (event === "SIGNED_IN") {
    client
      .from("table")
      .select("*")
      .then(({ data, error }) => {
        //if RLS is checking email or uid in the policy, this will not get the rows that match
      });
    client
      .channel("*")
      .on("postgres_changes", { event: "*", schema: "*" }, (payload) => {
        //this will work just fine, it passes the session to the api and gets notifications according to RLS
      })
      .subscribe();
  }
});

client.auth.signInWithPassword({email: 'insert valid email here', password: 'insert valid password here'});
```

## Expected behavior

The db api call should use the session that was just established

## System information

- OS: macOS
- Version of supabase-js: V2 RC 10
- Version of Node.js: v18.9.0

## Additional context

Since the exact same code works just fine in the browser, wIthout going deep into the sdk code, this looks like an issue with localStoarge not being available in node?
